<p>If you use double curly braces in code blocks in markdown with Jekyll. They just wonâ€™t show up.</p>

<p>Enclosed the code block in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">raw</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">endraw</code> tags. Like this:</p>

<p>{% raw % }
some code here
{% endraw % }</p>

<p>Writing the previous line and make it appear correctly in this blog post sent me to a 4-hour bottomless pit of googling. I think itâ€™s not possible to show the raw/endraw code in a code block using the raw/endraw tags. Basically I am trying to show:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>open raw tag
some code here
close raw tag
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>This is mostly used to show code that has double curly braces:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>{ {site.baseurl} }/assets/images/
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>I have also seen some strange behavior when adding a JavaScript code block and using Safari on mobile in Reader view mode. The HTML content is not displayed correctly. I thought that maybe my Jekyll template was broken and I tried testing the website in Chrome reading view</p>

